const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Are PT-141 and Melanotan the same thing?',
    a: 'No. They come from the same molecular family and are sold in the same grey market, which is why they get confused — but they are built for opposite jobs. Melanotan II is a tanning peptide (its main target is the pigment receptor MC1R); PT-141 (bremelanotide) was re-engineered from it to drop the tanning effect and keep the effect on sexual desire (MC4R).',
  },
  {
    q: 'Which one is FDA approved?',
    a: 'PT-141 is — as bremelanotide (Vyleesi), for hypoactive sexual desire disorder in premenopausal women. Melanotan II is not approved anywhere. The tanning peptide that did get approved is its cousin Melanotan I (afamelanotide / Scenesse), and only for a rare light-sensitivity disease, not cosmetic tanning.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does PT-141 make you tan?',
    a: 'Much less than Melanotan II, because it was specifically redesigned to minimise MC1R (pigment) activity. But it is not perfectly selective, so repeated use can still cause focal skin and gum darkening — the pigment effect resurfacing.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does Melanotan II affect libido?',
    a: 'Yes — that overlap is exactly where PT-141 came from. Melanotan II users frequently reported spontaneous arousal, and chemists chased that side effect into a separate drug. So both peptides touch both systems; they just differ in which effect they were built to maximise.',
  },
];

