<PageLayout
  title="PT-141 vs Melanotan: same family, opposite jobs"
  kicker="Comparison"
  description="PT-141 and Melanotan are constantly confused — they share a molecular family and a grey market. But one was built to tan you and one to affect desire. Here's the clean breakdown of what each is, which is approved, and how to tell them apart."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Bremelanotide', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bremelanotide'] },
    { name: 'Melanotan II', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanotan_II'] },
    { name: 'Afamelanotide', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afamelanotide'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'PT-141 (bremelanotide) and Melanotan II come from the same molecular family but were built for opposite jobs: PT-141 for sexual desire, Melanotan II for tanning.',
      'PT-141 is FDA-approved as Vyleesi for low sexual desire in premenopausal women; Melanotan II is not approved anywhere and is sold only on the grey market.',
      'PT-141 was engineered out of Melanotan II — chemists chased Melanotan II’s arousal side effect and stripped out most of the tanning activity.',
      'Neither peptide is perfectly selective: Melanotan II can raise libido, and PT-141 can still darken skin.',
      'A third name adds to the confusion — Melanotan I (afamelanotide / Scenesse) is the MC1R-selective cousin that became an approved medicine for a rare light-sensitivity disorder.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    Few pairs of peptides get mixed up as often as <strong>PT-141</strong> and
    <strong>Melanotan</strong>. They sound related, they're sold on the same sites in
    the same little vials, and they genuinely do come from the same molecular family.
    But they were built to do almost opposite things, and only one of them is an
    approved medicine. Here is the clean version.
  </p>

  <h2>The shared origin — why they're related at all</h2>
  <p>
    Both descend from α-MSH, the natural <a href="/system">melanocortin</a> peptide.
    <a href="/melanotan">Melanotan II</a> came first, designed as a non-selective
    agonist to drive <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> and produce a sunless tan.<Cite n={3} />
    In its early use, one side effect kept showing up: spontaneous sexual arousal.
    Rather than discard it, chemists re-worked the Melanotan II scaffold to strip out
    most of the pigment activity while keeping the pro-sexual effect — and the result
    was <a href="/bremelanotide">PT-141</a>, later approved as bremelanotide.<Cite n={1} />
    So PT-141 is, quite literally, one of Melanotan's side effects turned into its own
    drug.
  </p>

  <h2>Same family, opposite jobs</h2>
  <div class="not-prose my-8 overflow-x-auto">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b-2 border-[var(--border)] text-left align-bottom">
          <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-[var(--muted)]"></th>
          <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-[var(--text)]">Melanotan II</th>
          <th class="py-2 font-semibold text-[var(--text)]">PT-141 (bremelanotide)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="align-top">
        <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border)]">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-[var(--muted)]">Built for</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 text-[var(--text)]">Tanning (sunless pigment)</td>
          <td class="py-2 text-[var(--text)]">Sexual desire</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border)]">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-[var(--muted)]">Main receptor</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 text-[var(--text)]">MC1R (pigment)</td>
          <td class="py-2 text-[var(--text)]">MC4R (central arousal)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border)]">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-[var(--muted)]">FDA approved?</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 text-[var(--text)]">No — grey market only</td>
          <td class="py-2 text-[var(--text)]">Yes — as Vyleesi (HSDD in premenopausal women)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border)]">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-[var(--muted)]">Approved form</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 text-[var(--text)]">None</td>
          <td class="py-2 text-[var(--text)]">1.75 mg subcutaneous autoinjector</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-[var(--muted)]">Signature risks</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 text-[var(--text)]">Darkening &amp; changing moles, nausea, unregulated purity</td>
          <td class="py-2 text-[var(--text)]">Nausea, transient blood-pressure rise, focal darkening</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>
    The table hides one subtlety worth stating plainly: <em>both</em> peptides touch
    <em>both</em> systems, because neither is perfectly selective. Melanotan II can
    stir libido; PT-141 can still darken skin.<Cite n={2} /> The difference is which effect
    each was engineered to maximise and which to suppress — not that either one is
    clean.
  </p>

  <h2>Don't forget the third name: Melanotan I</h2>
  <p>
    Part of the confusion is that "Melanotan" itself refers to two different things.
    <strong>Melanotan I</strong> is the MC1R-selective version — and it is the one
    that actually became a medicine, as <a href="/therapeutics#afamelanotide">afamelanotide
    (Scenesse)</a>, approved for a rare light-sensitivity disorder rather than
    cosmetic tanning. <strong>Melanotan II</strong> is the non-selective,
    grey-market tanning peptide. So the family has one approved tanning drug
    (Melanotan I, narrow use), one approved desire drug (PT-141), and one unapproved
    peptide sold for tanning (Melanotan II).
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    If you remember one thing: <strong>PT-141 is the approved desire drug; Melanotan
    II is the unapproved tanning peptide; they overlap because PT-141 was carved out
    of Melanotan II.</strong> The approved product (Vyleesi) is a regulated injection
    of known dose; the "PT-141" and "Melanotan" sold as research peptides are of
    unverified purity and carry real risks — a blood-pressure signal for PT-141, and
    for Melanotan II the added, specific concern that driving pigment cells can
    darken and change moles.<Cite n={4} /> Same family, very different footing.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--accent-soft)] p-6 text-sm leading-relaxed">
    <p class="font-medium text-[var(--text)]">Education, not a protocol</p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-[var(--text)]">
      This page explains how these peptides differ. It does not provide dosing,
      sourcing, or usage instructions, and it is not medical advice or an endorsement
      of unapproved use. See the <a href="/about">editorial standards</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <FAQ items={faqs} />

  <References items={references} />
</PageLayout>
